Martin,

It looks like a mechanism problem.  You can see what the CVODE error is 
if you run MATLAB in a shell window, rather than through its graphical 
interface (although I don&#39;t know if this is possible in Windows). I do 
it by giving the command

matlab -nodisplay -nojvm -nosplash

When I run your matlab script in this way, I see the error message 
CVODE prints:

CVode-- At t=4.6612e-13 and step size h=3.52863e-19, the error test
failed repeatedly or with |h| = hmin.

This doesn&#39;t show up when running MATLAB the usual way, since CVODE 
prints this to the standard output, which MATLAB seems to ignore.

Anyway, this message means that CVODE is unable to take a step, even 
one as small as 10^-19 s. This usually occurs when some reaction has a 
huge rate, either due to some error in the mechanism,  or in some cases 
to initial conditions. (For example, starting with a composition of 
just H and O at 300 K might do this.)  In your case, it looks like one 
reaction has an extremely large reverse rate of progress - 10^17 
kmol/m3/s  (do &#39;rop_r(gas)&#39; in MATLAB to see this).  I suspect that 
this is causing your problems. It may be that the forward rate constant 
is too large, or that the thermochemistry for some species is in error.

Dave


